title: filletcube() OpenSCAD module
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This a module for OpenSCAD to create a cube with rounded edges (fillets). It doesn't use minkowski or hull, thus it renders fast (enought). Usage:
Like the build in module cube(), the first parameter is an array [x,y,z]
The second, third, and fourth parameters are for the side, top and bottom fillet radius.
They can be adresses with side=, top= and bottom=. Theese parameters work with arrays and take four values.
Each value is the radius of the fillet on an edge, counted clockwise.
The cube can be centered on each axis with the boolean parameters x, y and z
or all together with center.
The variable "filletcuberesolution" is the length of each segment of the round edges.
That means a smaller filletcuberesolution value equals more detail!
Caution: if you choose a very small filletcuberesolution OpenSCAD will work quite hard as the $fn will rise!
Each parameter except the first (dimensions of the cube) is optional.

The ultimate in Bezier curviness in OpenScad is to have thickness of surface, without having to use a bazillion granules to render an object. This thing is some updating of the bezier functions to deal with the mesh better. Specifically, you can hand the BezierMesh() module a set of 4 Bezier curves, and it will do the surface interpolation/tesselation, and generate a mesh of triangle patches that will represent the surface. I labelled this as version '0.5' because there are some pretty horrible bugs. As can be seen in the first picture, those blue dots are the calculated surface normals for each of the quad faces. There is a flaw in the rotation angle calculations such that there is a bias, which causes the normals to point off axis in the wrong direction depending on this and that. On more interesting meshes, this will show up even worse. Also, there are still cracks between the 'rows' as I am not properly calculating the lengths of the sides to match up properly. I know what needs to be done, but I was trying to get the normals right first. I'm releasing this now, even though it's not quite functional, because I want other people to take a look and possibly do the math better than I am. It's all really straight forward actually. Nothing too harry other than getting some trig right. The rest is just multiplication and addition. Easy optimizations abound, particularly in the BezierMesh() module. The first, to speed up processing, would be to separate the Bezier coefficient calculations from the general 'pointoncurve' calculation. That would be way efficient. There are some updated functions in the 'maths.scad' file, as well as the 'Render2D.scad' file. For the final, I'll separate out the "render" stuff for granules from the core drawing. The ideal would be that you could drop in your own renderer, and get totally different behavior. I think that's a fairly easy way to extend OpenScad. At any rate, just a step along the path... UPDATE: Here's a blog entry to go with it...
http://williamaadams.wordpress.com/2011/05/19/mr-beziers-new-perspective/

1) Download OpenScad files to a directory
2) Load up 'demo_bezmesh.scad'
3) Play around with it
4) Fix my horrible bugs
5) Rejoice!

description.text:
Dear family and friends,  
My name is Justin and I am in the process of earning the rank of Eagle Scout in the Boy Scouts of America.  I am also a member of Order of the Arrow, the Boy Scout Honor Society.  I have been involved in scouting since first grade.  Some of the many skills I have learned through scouting are camping, outdoor care where I am a certified Leave No Trace counselor, and leadership.   
My Eagle project is to design, build and install handicapped accessible benches and picnic tables at property in South Park, Colorado that is run by the non-profit group, Trout Unlimited.    I would like everyone to have access to the outdoors and be able to participate in outdoor sports without limitation.  The picnic table will be wheelchair accessible and the fishing benches equipped with rod holders to help all people enjoy this wonderful piece of property.   
My Eagle project is fully approved by my unit, district and council, and I am fundraising right now to secure money to pay for the materials and supplies for my project.  I am starting to build in March 2015, with installation slated for June. If YOU would like to help me and donate to my project that would be a huge blessing! You can identify yourself or remain anonymous, and ALL monies are going to my project and beneficiary - my reward is knowing I've made a difference and touched someone's life in a positive way, helping them enjoy the outdoors without limitations.  
Have a great day & THANK YOU SO MUCH to my family & friends who have supported me in my time as a Scout, and for coming together to help me with my Eagle Project!

Open your beers, I will! This yoda bottle opener is based on the existing yoda figurines, and looks like one too when standing, but has a bottle opener on the bottom.

I took existing Yoda STLs and simplified the mesh in meshlab, from 400k to 10k faces. I did this so I could import it in solidworks, and it is slightly noticable, but not too bad. Once I had it in solidworks,I added the bottle opener feature on the bottom, which was based on previous bottle openers I have made and tested (one Bucky Badger bottle opener, which I have not published here yet). I have not tested this one yet, hence I have left this a work in progress, and I will likely continue to modify this as i test it and improve it.
To print this, I used replicatorG, where I rotated it and used "full support" on the inside bottle opener cavity. UPDATE 1: current geometry fits bottle correctly. also, I added a bottle fit testing piece, which you can print to make sure it will fit on top of the bottle before you print the full yoda. UPDATE 2: Yoda has been tested, albeit not as thoroughly as I might like. Yoda should work. continue to stand by for more testing if you are still hesitant. UPDATE 3: after some thorough testing Yoda worked for several months of use, but eventually the opener cracked along the horizontally printed plane. printed at what i believe to be 30% infill, with 3 shells, so kick the infill up and it should be fine. I will reprint and continue testing. additionally, after several uses, it became slightly more difficult to use, as the lip degraded. I am not sure exactly what I need to do to fix this, so I may be updating the file. UPDATE 4: printed it again at 60% infill, and 3 shells. seems to be working like a charm. feel free to continue standing by for more updates as i continue to put it to the test! :D

One of the most beloved characters from Monument Valley! Each cube of Totem can be turned independently. I'll paint one soon to post! Update June 5th
In my excitement to post my first design fully-made in TinkerCAD, the initial version contained pins a hair too big. The files have just been adjusted from 8.10mm to 7.70mm, so now everything should work great.

You could use the default settings of 10% infill with two shells, but I only used 5% infill with two shells, and it still turned out great.  No raft needed.  
When all four cubes and pins are printed, just pop in a connector pin into the cylindrical hole. It's a snug fit, so a tiny bit of force is required, but the cubes should not shake loose when assembled.

At my thing-o-matic there was some vibration of the y stage wood at certain y stage speeds. It turned out that one of the simplest parts in the world could fix this vibration. This reduced the noise during printing quite considerably. Would be nice if it also does so for someone else.
Just print it and clamp it from below to the y stage on the left side near the x stage stepper motor (no disassembly needed). You might need a knife to make it fit.

comments.text: The problem you are seeing is that the optical endstops you have terminate in a Molex SL (aka Dupont) connector, however the MKS Base has JST-XH board connectors.  The contact length of the pins of a JST-XH connector is significantly shorter than that used on the Molex SL connector, which is why they were falling off too easily, as they don't have a long enough contact surface (and the Molex SL housings do not mate with the JST-XH sockets on the board).

title: Square Vase, Cup, and Bracelet Generator

description.text:
Let your imagination run wild stacking squares.  With essentially an infinite number of choices in the customizer you can be assured no one will have an object just like your's.  By changing the dimensions you can make planters, trays, bud vases, pencil holders, bracelets, or drinking glasses.  The simpler smaller objects make good demonstration pieces and will print quite quickly.  
Update: Moved max layers from 200 to 800.  Careful with the higher layers it could result in long renders.  Also added a control to force the design to be hollow if you can't do it in your slicer.

Run the customizer and choose your parameters and export the STL.  Be careful to avoid large overhangs.  It is quite possible to use the customizer to create something unprintable.  When slicing specify no fill and no top layers.  Once you print it, be sure to upload a photo. I'm curious to see what people end up with. I have several other vase customizers with variations on this theme.  Check out the "Derived from" to see the other versions.

comments.author: Leo_Aguiar

comments.text: It will render in half the time if you don't force hollow and instead slice it hollow with your slicer. You'll be able to control the wall width too doing this which will give you more control over not having spaces between the layers. The render time should be directly proportional to layersdouble spiral (1,2)squares per layer*force hollow(1,2).
comments.author: Leo_Aguiar

comments.text: Thanks for the tip! I use Slic3r. Would the wall width be defined by the number of perimeters then?
comments.author: Eckerput

comments.text: Yup, the number of perimeters determines the wall thickness.  Since you are making a vase, be sure to set bottom layers to how thick you want the bottom, zero infill, and no top layers.  The force hollow vase makes 2 mm walls, so you'll want to go higher than that for your walls if you saw gaps on the customizer STL.

description.text:
This is a bottle cooler shaped to fit Sodastream glass bottles.
It was inspired by JamieLaing's Wine Cooler but wanted to have a perfect fit for all the Sodastream bottles we have. I've added some other versions now:
No. 5: square outside shape, gives you more space to fill in the ice in the corners.
No. 6: like No. 5 but with round edges.
No. 7: like No. 6 but with stronger support between the inner and outer wall.
No. 7: I've also added another one with no wholes between ice compartment and bottle area. It should keep you bottle dry (not sure if it works; condensation?) but has probably less cooling efficiency. I didn't try it so far. Any feedback would be apprechiated. And finally now there is also a cap that helps filling in the ice. Just put it on the inner circle and drop the ice and some water over it. No more ice will be falling into the bottle area. ;-)

For my printer I've had to split the cooler into 3 parts. That's why No.7 helped me as in each part, the inner and outer walls were connected. I've printed the cooler with 50% infill, less would probably be also fine.
The ice infill cap can be printed with very little infill.

description.text:
my OpenSCAD library to stop wasting so much time on stupid things like forgetting not to write cylinder([L,W,H]) and positionning amongst other things. I will not lie: this library aims to replace the cube() function ; it ttreats all basic solids (cubes and variations of the prismatic cylinder) the same way when it comes to positionning (the cylinder is enclosed in the box defined by the cube of same paramters). Elliptical cylinders are made available, as well as "clavette" and
hollow prisms. PARAMETERS
  • fn number of faces. 0 is a special case for the cube, it defaults to this base "box" in which to fit the solid. same as cube() parameters
  • center whether to center the solid on each axis. defaults to [true,true,false], which is the default behaviour of the cylinder, while [false,false,false] will mimic the behabiour of the cube() function
  • oblong do we treat an elongated cylinder as an ellipse (false) or as a hull() of two smaller cylinders (true, default).
  • zrot makes sense only if "oblong" is turned on. the rotation for each of the two hull cylinders on their own z axis. this allows you to create cool shapes and fix some issues at the same time.
  • shell defaults to 0, a full (non-hollow) solid. higher values will create some sort of extruded tube.
    • LIMITATIONS/FEATURES prism(5,[20,40,10],shell=5) != rotate([0,0,90]) prism([40,20,10],shell=5)
  • thickness of the shell will not always be the constant along the perimeter. patches welcome.
  • rounded corners would be a nice addition too

title: HIC Prusa i3 Custom Firmware/ bed level/ metal to metal zmin

description.text:
Updated firmware for the HIC prusa. It has the auto bed leveling feature, but not the servo arm feature. the reason for this is that i used the method of splicing the z endstop wires to the aluminum bed, and the other to the x carriage ( as long as it makes contact with metal hotend). when these two make contact, the zmin is triggered. this method seems to work flawlesly with my machine, however, if you find an error, please let me know so that i can update mine too. If you just want the firmware without the auto bed leveling, just add a "//" to the front of "#define ENABLE_AUTO_BED_LEVELING" video:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rS_nvMX6wzM&feature=youtube_gdata

• the metal to metal zmin requires the removal of the z switch stop. the connector is the only thing needed to do this mod.

  • An aluminum bed is also required for it to work properly.

  • with the endstop cut off, solder or crimp a closed ring to both wire ends. You might have to make the wires longer to get proper clearances for travel.

  • one closed ring goes to your x carriage (assuming it is metal like mine, and that it makes metal to metal contact with the hotend.) and the other goes to the aluminum hotbed.

  • tuck your wires neatly and make sure they clear the travel.

  • to enable the auto bed leveling feature you MUST add the command line G29 right after G28 on your start/end gcode.
    if the code G28 is followed by X0 Y0 delete those values so that only G28 remains
    if there is a separate G28 code followed by Z0, delete the whole line so that it looks as follows:
    • G28
    G29
    plain and simple..;) TIPS:
    -once the measuring of the bed level begins, you can add elmers glue on the aluminum, i have found this method to work without all the blue tape mess. -pay special attention to the begining of the process, make sure the nozzle is clear of plastic. use tweezers or sandpaper to keep it clean, as it is critical to get the correct reading. -i have found 180 degrees to work good without any seepage of plastic. i will post a video soon, depending on requests. :)

description.text:
This is parametric pot stirrer.
It has a 12V motor attached to the top of the shaft (10RPM from ebay) which rests on the top of the pot. It runs off an adaptor, but could easily run off batteries depending on how much power is required to run it. To enable quick and easy detachment of the motor from the stirrer it uses a modified version of my Parametric spider coupling inspired by the Turbo Mixer. The spider is not required, as with one-way rotation backlash is not an issue The default current stirrer is designed for an 11cm flat base pot, but this can be easily adjusted in the SCAD file. EDIT 16/6/13:
New SCAD uploaded with a few more options for the hub attachment.
My initial version distorted while cooking porridge, and the blades were too close, so tended to clog with a range of things (rice,lentils,etc) so I've spaced them out a bit more.
I'm unsure whether I'll be able to change the profile to stop the heat-distortion, or whether I'll just have to cast it in something a bit more heat-proof or try nylon printing...
I covered the plastic overhanging the edge of the pot with Kapton, and that survived fine.

Print the parts
Vitamins:
Motor (12V DC 10RPM high torque)
Batteries and holder, or DC power supply
Aluminium struts (10x10mm used in print, but edit the scad for whatever profile you like. I ultimately used m8 threaded rod as I had some lying around.
M3 nuts and screws to fix the struts to the motor and the supports to the struts
M8 shaft and a couple of nuts (optional self-locking as above) to go in the coupler and blades. It may be possible to print the shaft attached to the blades, but I'm not sure if it will withstand the shearing rotation if printed vertically attached to the blade. Drill holes in the struts at varying locations to enable use with a number of different sized pots - just move supports along depending on the size of the pot/container. Different sizes of stirrers can be made depending on container size - as long as the jaw coupling is the same size the one motor/topend will drive them all. Happy stirring...

description.text: Let your imagination run wild stacking polygons.  With essentially an infinite number of choices  in the customizer you can be assured no one will have an object just like your's.  By changing the dimensions you can make planters, trays, bud vases, pencil holders, bracelets, or drinking glasses.  The simpler smaller objects make good demonstration pieces and will print quite quickly.

Run the customizer and choose your parameters.  The key parameter to have different polygons is the smoothness value. Be careful to avoid large overhangs. It is quite possible to use the customizer to create something unprintable. When slicing specify no fill and no top layers. Once you print it, be sure to upload a photo. I'm curious to see what people end up with. I have several other vase customizers with variations on this theme. Check out the "Derived from" to see the other versions.  
I like to make bracelets when changing filament color.  That is why they are multicolor.  I find it a good way to clean out the nozzle and my daughter likes them.

I took jwags55's design, lengthened it to that of a AA (so I didn't have to print two for each battery) and increased the twist (just for aesthetics). For the hollow model, I changed the wall to .525mm so that I could print it nicely as a vase with my .35mm nozzle. Also, I uploaded a solid model as requested in the original comments. Autodesk Inventor source file included for the solid model. Edit 6/5/2015
I added a double and triple adapter to the lot. I needed this for a flashlight that had three "C"s stacked end-to-end and thought it would be nice to have one continuous adapter for it.

Printed on my Prusa I3.
Sliced using Slic3r
